The setup is as follows: my experiment runs in PsychoPy using the code from PyCodeFin, and it runs in parallel with a wireless EEG headset (Unicorn Hybrid Black). My code saves all task responses into a CSV file. It also sends specific triggers to the Unicorn headset software, which we use as timestamps in the EEG recording. In other words, when an image appears on the screen during the PsychoPy task, a corresponding trigger appears in the EEG recording.

This is where the problem comes in: although the trigger appears in the live recording, it is not saved in the final CSV file generated by the Unicorn Recorder software. In the trigger column, the entire column contains only 0, as if no triggers had been sent at all.

For this issue, I think lines 95–96 should probably be modified (The code sends the trigger as ASCII over UDP to Unicorn Recorder. Example: 1 → b"1".).
I separately used a simplified version of the code to see what I could change in order to send triggers that would actually appear correctly. One of the problems was, for example, that .encode("ascii") does not support certain characters, such as 321. For simple numbers (e.g. 3, 2, 1), the triggers appeared correctly and were also saved in the EEG CSV file. The simplified version is included below.

import socket
import time

UDP_IP = "127.0.0.1"
UDP_PORT = 1000

sock = socket.socket(socket.AF_INET, socket.SOCK_DGRAM)
endpoint = (UDP_IP, UDP_PORT)
codes = [1, 2, 3, 321]

for code in codes:
    code_encoded = str(code).encode()
    sock.sendto(code_encoded, endpoint)
    time.sleep(0.05)   # 50 ms activ
    sock.sendto(b"0", endpoint)
    time.sleep(1.0)

sock.close()
print("Gata.")

When I tried to integrate the modified version into the main code, I noticed that it no longer recorded even the EEG data in the CSV file. In other words, data storage stopped at the moment the experiment started, even though the program continued running live. 
